The paper deals with program verification techniques, which typically fall under the category of formal methods. The use of real algebraic geometry and SDP optimization suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO). The paper also deals with synthesis of polynomial interpolants, which is a common technique in program verification, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY). Additionally, the paper mentions continued fraction-based algorithms, which are often used in numerical analysis and optimization, suggesting that the paper may belong to the sub-category of Scientific Computing (cs.SC). The paper also deals with theoretical observations in real algebraic geometry, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) or Computational Geometry (cs.CG).
